\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, test functions are all Fourier transformable since they are absolute-integr
able (they die off at infinitely very fast).
 But is the Fourier transform of a test function also a test function?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a test function, then so is its Fourier transform, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}\left(k\right):=\int dxe^{-ikx}F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\textnormal{th}}$
\end_inset

 derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{F}\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{F}^{\left(p\right)}\left(k\right):=\frac{d^{p}}{dk^{p}}\hat{F}\left(k\right)=\left(-i\right)^{p}\indefint xx^{p}F\left(x\right)e^{-ikx}=\left(-i\right)^{p}\mathcal{F}\left[x^{p}F\left(x\right)\right]\left(k\right)
\]

\end_inset

 By the two remarks above, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{p}F\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is a test function, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\left[x^{p}F\left(x\right)\right]\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 exists.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|\hat{F}^{\left(p\right)}\left(k\right)\right| & = & \left|\indefint xx^{p}F\left(x\right)e^{-ikx}\right|\\
 & = & \left|\indefint xx^{p}F\left(x\right)\frac{1}{-ik}\frac{d}{dx}e^{-ikx}\right|
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Integrating by parts (the boundary term vanishes since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a test function):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\left|\hat{F}^{\left(p\right)}\left(k\right)\right|=\left|\frac{1}{-ik}\indefint xe^{-ikx}\frac{d}{dx}\left(x^{p}F\left(x\right)\right)\right|.
\]

\end_inset

We can do this again to pile on more derivatives onto 
